PneumoScan - Automated Pneumonia Detection in Chest X-Rays Using Convolutional Neural Networks¶

Group 9:

  • Ifediorah, Kenechukwu (9052693)
  • Owulu, Amarachukwu (8923561)

Objective:

The objective of this project is to develop and implement a convolutional neural network (CNN) model capable of accurately detecting pneumonia from chest X-ray images, fine-tune existing pre-trained models and compare the outcomes and performances. This system aims to:

  • Explore the effectiveness of various CNN architectures in medical image classification tasks
  • Evaluate the model's performance using standard metrics such as accuracy, precision-recall curve, etc

This project has significant real-world applications in healthcare settings, potentially reducing diagnostic time, improving resource allocation, and enhancing patient outcomes through earlier and more accurate pneumonia detection.

About the Dataset

The dataset for this project is obtained from Chest X-Ray Immages (Pneumonia)

***Note:** The dataset used in this project complies with the health-ethical rules and is suitable for use as a license.*

Contextual Summary:

Figure S6. Illustrative Examples of Chest X-Rays in Patients with Pneumonia, Related to Figure 6

The normal chest X-ray (left panel) depicts clear lungs without any areas of abnormal opacification in the image. Bacterial pneumonia (middle) typically exhibits a focal lobar consolidation, in this case in the right upper lobe (white arrows), whereas viral pneumonia (right) manifests with a more diffuse ‘‘interstitial’’ pattern in both lungs.

http://www.cell.com/cell/fulltext/S0092-8674(18)30154-530154-5)

Content:

The dataset is organized into 3 folders (train, test, val) and contains subfolders for each image category (Pneumonia/Normal). There are 5,863 X-Ray images (JPEG) and 2 categories (Pneumonia/Normal).

Chest X-ray images (anterior-posterior) were selected from retrospective cohorts of pediatric patients of one to five years old from Guangzhou Women and Children’s Medical Center, Guangzhou. All chest X-ray imaging was performed as part of patients’ routine clinical care.

For the analysis of chest x-ray images, all chest radiographs were initially screened for quality control by removing all low quality or unreadable scans. The diagnoses for the images were then graded by two expert physicians before being cleared. In order to account for any grading errors, the evaluation set was also checked by a third expert.

In [8]:
# Function to extract all labels from the dataset
def get_labels(dataset):
    all_labels = []
    for _, labels in dataset:
        all_labels.append(labels.numpy())
    return np.concatenate(all_labels)
In [9]:
train_labels = get_labels(train_dataset)
val_labels = get_labels(validation_dataset)
test_labels = get_labels(test_dataset)

train, train_count = np.unique(train_labels, return_counts=True)
val, val_count = np.unique(val_labels, return_counts=True)
test, test_count = np.unique(test_labels, return_counts=True)


# Print the distribution
for label, count in zip(train, train_count):
    label = "Normal" if label == 0 else "Pneumonia"
    print(f"Train Class {label}: {count} images ({count/len(train_labels):.2%})")
for label, count in zip(val, val_count):
    label =  "Normal" if label == 0 else "Pneumonia"
    print(f"Validation Class {label}: {count} images ({count/len(val_labels):.2%})")
for label, count in zip(test, test_count):
    label =  "Normal" if label == 0 else "Pneumonia"
    print(f"Test Class {label}: {count} images ({count/len(test_labels):.2%})")

def get_label_name(label):
    return 'Normal' if label == 0 else 'Pneumonia'

fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(20, 5))

axes[0].bar([get_label_name(label) for label in train], train_count)
axes[0].set_title('Class Distribution in Training Dataset')
axes[0].set_xlabel('Class')
axes[0].set_ylabel('Number of Images')

axes[1].bar([get_label_name(label) for label in val], val_count)
axes[1].set_title('Class Distribution in Validation Dataset')
axes[1].set_xlabel('Class')
axes[1].set_ylabel('Number of Images')

axes[2].bar([get_label_name(label) for label in test], test_count)
axes[2].set_title('Class Distribution in Test Dataset')
axes[2].set_xlabel('Class')
axes[2].set_ylabel('Number of Images')
plt.show();

We notice that there is an equal proportion of split between classes in both testing, training and validation datasets. This has been intentionally prepared this way. However, we still have class imbalance, with Normal images being just above 25% of the total dataset and Pneumonial images taking up about 75%.

Now we'll visualize the images to see what they look like

In [17]:
fig, axes = plt.subplots(3, 5, figsize=(20, 16))
axes = axes.ravel()

for ax, i in zip(axes, np.random.choice(range(30), 20)):
    label = "Normal" if train_labels_batch[i] == 0 else "Pneumonia"
    ax.imshow(train_data_batch[i].numpy().astype("uint8"))
    ax.axis("off") 
    ax.set_title(f"Label for image {i}: {label}")

From the human eye, only trained medical professionals would be able to identify the difference between these images. To a random person, they'll most likely look the same. We will feed the images and labels to our CNN model to learn and be able to predict.

The class imbalance is quite obvious from the random selection with the number of the pneumonia class we can see

Befofe this however, we will perform some augmentation on the data like flipping, rotation, zooming, etc., to make sure that the model is able to capture the features and characteristics, regardless of the orientation of the image.

2. Data Augmentation¶

In [12]:
# Define the augmentation layer
data_augmentation_layer = keras.Sequential(
    [
        keras.layers.RandomRotation(0.2),
        keras.layers.RandomZoom(0.2),
        keras.layers.RandomTranslation(0.1, 0.1),
    ]
)

Now we'll display some augmented images to see the effects of the data augmentation layers on the input images

In [19]:
plt.figure(figsize=(20, 8))
for images, _ in train_dataset.take(1):
    for i in range(8):
        augmented_images = data_augmentation_layer(images)
        ax = plt.subplot(2, 4, i + 1)
        plt.imshow(augmented_images[0].numpy().astype("uint8"))
        plt.axis("off")

3. Building the CNN Model¶

In [20]:
inputs = keras.Input(shape=(512, 512, 3))
x = data_augmentation_layer(inputs)
x = layers.Rescaling(1./255)(x)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters = 32 , kernel_size = 3, padding = 'same' , activation = 'relu')(x)
x = layers.BatchNormalization()(x)
x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size = 2)(x)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters = 32 , kernel_size = 3, padding = 'same' , activation = 'relu')(x)
x = layers.Dropout(0.1)(x)
x = layers.BatchNormalization()(x)
x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size = 2)(x)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters = 64 , kernel_size = 3, padding = 'same' , activation = 'relu')(x)
x = layers.Dropout(0.1)(x)
x = layers.BatchNormalization()(x)
x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size = 2)(x)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters = 64 , kernel_size = 3 , padding = 'same' , activation = 'relu')(x)
x = layers.Dropout(0.2)(x)
x = layers.BatchNormalization()(x)
x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size = 2)(x)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters = 128 , kernel_size = 3 , padding = 'same' , activation = 'relu')(x)
x = layers.Dropout(0.2)(x)
x = layers.BatchNormalization()(x)
x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size = 2)(x)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters = 128 , kernel_size = 3 , padding = 'same' , activation = 'relu')(x)
x = layers.Dropout(0.3)(x)
x = layers.BatchNormalization()(x)
x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size = 2)(x)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters = 256 , kernel_size = 3 , padding = 'same' , activation = 'relu')(x)
x = layers.Flatten()(x)
x = layers.Dense(units = 128 , activation = 'relu')(x)
x = layers.Dropout(0.5)(x)
outputs = layers.Dense(units = 1 , activation = 'sigmoid')(x)
model = keras.Model(inputs, outputs)

model.summary()

In [23]:
model.compile(
    loss="binary_crossentropy",
    optimizer="adam",
    metrics=["accuracy"]
)

callbacks = [
    keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint(
        filepath="/kaggle/working/best_cnn_adam.keras",
        save_best_only=True,
        monitor="val_loss"
    ),
    
    # Early stopping to prevent overfitting
    EarlyStopping(
        monitor='val_loss',
        patience=10,               # Stop if no improvement for 10 epochs
        restore_best_weights=True  # Restore model to the best epoch
    ),
    
    # Learning rate reduction when plateauing
    ReduceLROnPlateau(
        monitor='val_loss',
        factor=0.5,                # Reduce LR by half
        patience=3,                # Wait 5 epochs before reducing
        min_lr=1e-6                # Don't go below this LR
    )
]

history = model.fit(
    train_dataset,
    epochs=50,
    validation_data=validation_dataset,
    callbacks=callbacks
)

In [28]:
model.compile(
    loss="binary_crossentropy",
    optimizer="rmsprop",
    metrics=["accuracy"]
)

callbacks = [
    keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint(
        filepath="/kaggle/working/best_cnn_rms.keras",
        save_best_only=True,
        monitor="val_loss"
    ),
    
    # Early stopping to prevent overfitting
    EarlyStopping(
        monitor='val_loss',
        patience=10,               # Stop if no improvement for 10 epochs
        restore_best_weights=True  # Restore model to the best epoch
    ),
    
    # Learning rate reduction when plateauing
    ReduceLROnPlateau(
        monitor='val_loss',
        factor=0.5,                # Reduce LR by half
        patience=3,                # Wait 5 epochs before reducing
        min_lr=1e-6                # Don't go below this LR
    )
]

history = model.fit(
    train_dataset,
    epochs=50,
    validation_data=validation_dataset,
    callbacks=callbacks
)

In [17]:
inputs = keras.Input(shape=(512, 512, 3))
x = data_augmentation_layer(inputs)
x = layers.Rescaling(1./255)(x)
x = mobilenet_base(x)
x = layers.GlobalAveragePooling2D()(x)
x = layers.Dropout(0.2)(x)
x = layers.Dense(units = 128 , activation = 'sigmoid')(x)
outputs = layers.Dense(units = 1 , activation = 'sigmoid')(x)
mobilenet_model = keras.Model(inputs, outputs)

In [19]:
mobilenet_model.compile(
    loss="binary_crossentropy",
    optimizer="rmsprop",
    metrics=["accuracy"]
)

callbacks = [
    keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint(
        filepath="/kaggle/working/best_mnet_rms.keras",
        save_best_only=True,
        monitor="val_loss"
    ),
    
    # Early stopping to prevent overfitting
    EarlyStopping(
        monitor='val_loss',
        patience=10,               # Stop if no improvement for 10 epochs
        restore_best_weights=True  # Restore model to the best epoch
    ),
    
    # Learning rate reduction when plateauing
    ReduceLROnPlateau(
        monitor='val_loss',
        factor=0.5,                # Reduce LR by half
        patience=3,                # Wait 5 epochs before reducing
        min_lr=1e-6                # Don't go below this LR
    )
]

history = mobilenet_model.fit(
    train_dataset,
    epochs=50,
    validation_data=validation_dataset,
    callbacks=callbacks
)

# Loading the MobileNet model
mnet_base2 =  MobileNetV2(
    weights="imagenet",
    include_top=False,
    input_shape=(224, 224, 3))

mnet_base2.trainable = False
In [29]:
def get_features_and_labels(dataset):
    all_features = []
    all_labels = []
    for images, labels in dataset:
        preprocessed_images = preprocess_input(images)
        features = mnet_base2.predict(preprocessed_images)
        all_features.append(features)
        all_labels.append(labels)
    return np.concatenate(all_features), np.concatenate(all_labels)

train_features_new, train_labels_new =  get_features_and_labels(train_dataset_new)
val_features_new, val_labels_new =  get_features_and_labels(validation_dataset_new)
test_features_new, test_labels_new =  get_features_and_labels(test_dataset_new)

In [37]:
# Define the augmentation layer
data_augmentation_layer_new = keras.Sequential(
    [
        keras.layers.RandomRotation(0.2),
        keras.layers.RandomZoom(0.2),
        keras.layers.RandomTranslation(0.1, 0.1),
        keras.layers.RandomContrast(0.1),
    ]
)
In [38]:
inputs = keras.Input(shape=(224, 224, 3))
x = data_augmentation_layer_new(inputs)
x = preprocess_input(x)
x = mnet_base2(x)
x = layers.GlobalAveragePooling2D()(x)
x = layers.Dropout(0.2)(x)
x = layers.Dense(units = 128 , activation = 'sigmoid')(x)
outputs = layers.Dense(units = 1 , activation = 'sigmoid')(x)
mnet_model = keras.Model(inputs, outputs)

        monitor='val_loss',
        patience=10,               # Stop if no improvement for 10 epochs
        restore_best_weights=True  # Restore model to the best epoch
    ),
    
    # Learning rate reduction when plateauing
    ReduceLROnPlateau(
        monitor='val_loss',
        factor=0.5,                # Reduce LR by half
        patience=3,                # Wait 5 epochs before reducing
        min_lr=1e-6                # Don't go below this LR
    )
]

history = mnet_model.fit(
    train_dataset_new,
    epochs=50,
    class_weight={0: class_weights[0], 1: class_weights[1]},
    validation_data=validation_dataset_new,
    callbacks=callbacks
)

train_accuracy_mnet_adam = history.history["accuracy"]
val_accuracy_mnet_adam = history.history["val_accuracy"]
train_loss_mnet_adam = history.history["loss"]
val_loss_mnet_adam = history.history["val_loss"]

fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(16, 5))
axes = axes.ravel()

epochs = range(1, len(train_accuracy_mnet_adam) + 1)
axes[0].plot(epochs, train_accuracy_mnet_adam, "bo", label="Training accuracy")
axes[0].plot(epochs, val_accuracy_mnet_adam, "b", label="Validation accuracy")
axes[0].set_title("Training and validation accuracy")
axes[0].legend()
axes[1].plot(epochs, train_loss_mnet_adam, "bo", label="Training loss")
axes[1].plot(epochs, val_loss_mnet_adam, "b", label="Validation loss")
axes[1].set_title("Training and validation loss")
axes[1].legend()
plt.show()

# --- Convert test dataset to NumPy arrays ---
test_images_list_new = []
test_labels_list_new = []

for images, labels in test_dataset_new:
    test_images_list_new.append(images.numpy())
    test_labels_list_new.append(labels.numpy())

test_images_new = np.concatenate(test_images_list_new)
test_labels_new = np.concatenate(test_labels_list_new)
